body:
When a function returns a reference, Rust needs to know which input lifetime it's tied to. The compiler cannot always infer this.

```rust
// ERROR: missing lifetime specifier
fn longest(x: &str, y: &str) -> &str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}

// FIX: explicit lifetime annotation
fn longest<'a>(x: &'a str, y: &'a str) -> &'a str {
    if x.len() > y.len() { x } else { y }
}
```

The `'a` annotation tells Rust: the returned reference lives at least as long as the shorter of the two input lifetimes. Without this, the compiler cannot verify the reference won't dangle. Lifetime elision rules handle simple cases (one input reference, or `&self`), but multi-reference returns always need explicit annotations.

Trait objects (`dyn Trait`) use dynamic dispatch via a vtable, while generics (`impl Trait` or `<T: Trait>`) use static dispatch with monomorphization. Choosing wrong impacts performance and binary size.

```rust
// Static dispatch — monomorphized, zero-cost abstraction
fn process(item: &impl Display) {
    println!("{}", item);
}

// Dynamic dispatch — vtable lookup at runtime
fn process_dyn(item: &dyn Display) {
    println!("{}", item);
}

// Trait objects are required for heterogeneous collections
let items: Vec<Box<dyn Display>> = vec![
    Box::new(42),
    Box::new("hello"),
    Box::new(3.14),
];
```

Use generics when you need maximum performance and know types at compile time. Use `dyn Trait` when you need heterogeneous collections or want to reduce binary size from monomorphization bloat. Not all traits are object-safe — traits with associated types or `Self` in return position cannot be used as `dyn Trait`.

Async functions in Rust return a `Future` that does nothing until polled by an async runtime. You cannot just `.await` from `main()` without setting up tokio or async-std.

```rust
// ERROR: `await` is only allowed inside `async` functions
async fn fetch_data() -> String { "data".to_string() }

fn main() {
    let data = fetch_data().await; // compile error
}

// FIX: use tokio runtime
#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let data = fetch_data().await;
    println!("{}", data);
}

// Or manually create runtime (useful in library code)
fn main() {
    let rt = tokio::runtime::Runtime::new().unwrap();
    let data = rt.block_on(fetch_data());
    println!("{}", data);
}
```

A common gotcha is calling `block_on` from within an async context — tokio will panic with "cannot block inside async runtime". Use `tokio::task::spawn_blocking` to bridge sync code inside async, and `Runtime::block_on` only from truly synchronous contexts.

Rust closures infer whether to capture by reference, mutable reference, or by value based on how captured variables are used inside the closure body.

```rust
let name = String::from("Alice");

// Captures by immutable reference (&name) — implements Fn
let greet = || println!("Hello, {}", name);
greet();
println!("{}", name); // name still accessible

// Captures by mutable reference (&mut name) — implements FnMut
let mut count = 0;
let mut increment = || { count += 1; };
increment();

// Captures by value (moves name) — implements FnOnce
let consume = move || {
    println!("Taking ownership: {}", name);
    drop(name);
};
consume();
// println!("{}", name); // ERROR: name was moved
```

The `move` keyword forces capture by value — essential when the closure outlives the current scope (e.g., spawning threads or returning closures). Without `move`, a closure sent to `thread::spawn` would hold references to stack variables that get dropped.

Rust has multiple string types. Using the wrong one causes unnecessary allocations or confusing lifetime errors.

```rust
use std::borrow::Cow;

// &str — borrowed, immutable, zero-cost slice into existing data
fn greet(name: &str) { println!("Hello, {name}"); }

// String — owned, heap-allocated, growable
let owned: String = "hello".to_string();
let also_owned: String = String::from("hello");

// Cow<str> — clone-on-write, avoids allocation when not needed
fn maybe_uppercase(s: &str) -> Cow<str> {
    if s.chars().any(|c| c.is_lowercase()) {
        Cow::Owned(s.to_uppercase()) // allocates only when needed
    } else {
        Cow::Borrowed(s) // zero-cost borrow
    }
}
```

Rules of thumb: accept `&str` in function parameters (works with both `String` and `&str`). Return `String` when the function creates new data. Use `Cow<str>` when you sometimes need to allocate and sometimes don't — common in parsing, normalization, and escaping functions. Never store `&str` in structs unless you're prepared to deal with lifetime annotations.

A common misconception is that `unsafe` turns off Rust's safety guarantees. It only unlocks five specific capabilities — the rest of Rust's rules still apply.

```rust
unsafe {
    // These five things are allowed in unsafe blocks:
    // 1. Dereference raw pointers
    let ptr = &42 as *const i32;
    let val = *ptr;

    // 2. Call unsafe functions
    libc::getpid();

    // 3. Access/modify mutable static variables
    static mut COUNTER: i32 = 0;
    COUNTER += 1;

    // 4. Implement unsafe traits
    // 5. Access fields of unions
}

// The borrow checker STILL applies inside unsafe:
unsafe {
    let mut v = vec![1, 2, 3];
    let r = &v[0];
    v.push(4); // STILL AN ERROR — borrow checker is active
}
```

Unsafe is a contract: you promise the compiler that the operations you perform uphold Rust's safety invariants even though the compiler cannot verify them. Minimize unsafe surface area — wrap unsafe code in safe abstractions with well-defined invariants.

Pin is required for async/await because Futures may contain self-referential fields. Moving a pinned value would invalidate internal pointers.

```rust
use std::pin::Pin;
use std::future::Future;

// Futures are !Unpin by default — they cannot be moved after polling
async fn example() {
    let data = vec![1, 2, 3];
    some_async_fn(&data).await; // Future holds reference to `data`
    // If the Future moved in memory, &data would dangle
}

// Pin<Box<dyn Future>> is the heap-pinned pattern
fn returns_future() -> Pin<Box<dyn Future<Output = i32>>> {
    Box::pin(async { 42 })
}

// Most types are Unpin (moveable) — Pin has no effect on them
// Only self-referential types (like async Futures) need Pin
let mut x = 5;
let pinned = Pin::new(&mut x); // fine, i32: Unpin
```

You rarely construct `Pin` manually. `Box::pin()` and `tokio::pin!()` handle it. The key insight: if a type implements `Unpin`, pinning is a no-op. Most standard types are `Unpin`. Only compiler-generated Future types and explicit self-referential structs are `!Unpin`.

Rust's type system enforces thread safety at compile time. You cannot share mutable data across threads without wrapping it in `Arc<Mutex<T>>` or `Arc<RwLock<T>>`.

```rust
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;

let counter = Arc::new(Mutex::new(0));
let mut handles = vec![];

for _ in 0..10 {
    let counter = Arc::clone(&counter);
    handles.push(thread::spawn(move || {
        let mut num = counter.lock().unwrap();
        *num += 1;
        // MutexGuard dropped here, lock released
    }));
}

for handle in handles {
    handle.join().unwrap();
}
println!("Result: {}", *counter.lock().unwrap()); // 10
```

Gotcha: holding a `MutexGuard` across an `.await` point will cause the lock to be held across a suspension point, potentially deadlocking. Use `tokio::sync::Mutex` for async code instead of `std::sync::Mutex`. For read-heavy workloads, prefer `RwLock` which allows concurrent readers.

Rust macros are hygienic: variables defined inside a macro invocation don't collide with variables in the calling scope. But metavariable behavior has surprises.

```rust
macro_rules! make_var {
    () => {
        let x = 42; // This x is in the macro's hygiene context
    };
}

fn main() {
    make_var!();
    // println!("{}", x); // ERROR: x not found in this scope
}

// Fix: pass the identifier from the caller
macro_rules! make_var {
    ($name:ident) => {
        let $name = 42; // Uses caller's hygiene context
    };
}

fn main() {
    make_var!(x);
    println!("{}", x); // works: 42
}
```

Another gotcha: `macro_rules!` uses the scope where the macro is defined, not where it's invoked, for resolving types and paths. If your macro references a type like `Vec`, it must be in scope at the definition site. Use `$crate::` prefix for paths in library macros to ensure correct resolution regardless of the caller's imports.

Iterator adaptors like `map`, `filter`, and `take` are lazy. They build up a chain of transformations but don't execute until a consuming method is called.

```rust
let v = vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5];

// BUG: this does nothing!
v.iter().map(|x| {
    println!("Processing {}", x); // never prints
    x * 2
});
// warning: unused `Map` that must be used

// FIX: consume the iterator
let doubled: Vec<_> = v.iter().map(|x| x * 2).collect();

// Or use for_each for side effects
v.iter().for_each(|x| println!("Processing {}", x));

// Common consumers: collect(), sum(), count(), any(), all(),
// find(), fold(), for_each()
```

This laziness is intentional — it enables zero-cost abstractions. The compiler fuses the entire iterator chain into a single loop with no intermediate allocations. But forgetting to consume is a frequent source of bugs, especially when using `map` for side effects instead of `for_each`.

Rust `match` expressions must cover every possible variant. This is a feature, not a bug — the compiler catches unhandled cases at compile time.

```rust
enum Command {
    Start,
    Stop,
    Pause,
}

// ERROR: non-exhaustive patterns: `Pause` not covered
match cmd {
    Command::Start => println!("Starting"),
    Command::Stop => println!("Stopping"),
}

// FIX: cover all variants
match cmd {
    Command::Start => println!("Starting"),
    Command::Stop => println!("Stopping"),
    Command::Pause => println!("Pausing"),
}

// Or use a wildcard (but you lose compile-time exhaustiveness)
match cmd {
    Command::Start => println!("Starting"),
    _ => println!("Other"),
}
```

The real power shows when you add a new variant to the enum — every `match` without a wildcard will fail to compile, forcing you to handle the new case everywhere. This is why `_ =>` wildcards should be used sparingly — they silence the compiler's help. Use `#[non_exhaustive]` on public enums to force downstream crates to include a wildcard arm.

Serde's derive macros handle most serialization, but real-world JSON rarely matches Rust's naming conventions. Missing fields or renamed keys cause silent failures without the right attributes.

```rust
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};

#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Debug)]
#[serde(rename_all = "camelCase")] // converts snake_case fields to camelCase
struct ApiResponse {
    user_name: String,         // serialized as "userName"
    #[serde(rename = "type")]  // Rust keyword, must rename
    item_type: String,
    #[serde(default)]          // uses Default::default() if missing
    is_active: bool,
    #[serde(skip_serializing_if = "Option::is_none")]
    email: Option<String>,     // omitted from JSON if None
    #[serde(default = "default_page_size")]
    page_size: u32,
}

fn default_page_size() -> u32 { 20 }

// Handles: {"userName": "alice", "type": "admin"}
// Missing is_active defaults to false, missing email becomes None
```

Gotcha: `#[serde(deny_unknown_fields)]` rejects JSON with extra keys — useful for strict APIs but breaks forward compatibility. Use `#[serde(flatten)]` to capture extra fields into a `HashMap` for flexible schemas.

When using `tokio::select!`, all branches race concurrently but only one completes. The other futures are dropped, which means any work they started is cancelled.

```rust
use tokio::time::{sleep, Duration};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    tokio::select! {
        _ = sleep(Duration::from_secs(1)) => {
            println!("timeout");
        }
        result = fetch_data() => {
            println!("got data: {}", result);
        }
    }
    // If fetch_data() completes first, the sleep future is dropped
    // If sleep completes first, fetch_data() is CANCELLED mid-execution
}

// DANGER: database writes inside a cancellable future
async fn save_and_notify(db: &Pool) {
    db.execute("INSERT INTO logs ...").await; // might complete
    send_notification().await;                 // might get cancelled here!
    // If cancelled between these two, you have inconsistent state
}
```

To handle cancellation safely, use `tokio::spawn` to run critical operations in their own task (which won't be cancelled by `select!`), or wrap the critical section in `tokio::task::unconstrained` to prevent yielding at await points.

This error occurs when you try to take ownership of a value through a reference. References only borrow — they don't own.

```rust
struct User { name: String }

fn get_name(user: &User) -> String {
    user.name // ERROR: cannot move out of `user.name` which is behind a shared reference
}

// Fix 1: Clone the value
fn get_name(user: &User) -> String {
    user.name.clone()
}

// Fix 2: Return a reference instead
fn get_name(user: &User) -> &str {
    &user.name
}

// Fix 3: Take ownership of the struct
fn get_name(user: User) -> String {
    user.name
}
```

This error is especially common when iterating over a collection by reference and trying to return owned elements. Use `.cloned()` or `.to_owned()` on iterators, or restructure to use references throughout. If you see this with `Option` or `Result`, use `.as_ref()` to borrow the inner value instead of moving it.

This error appears when you try to send a non-`Send` type across thread boundaries, commonly when spawning async tasks.

```rust
use std::rc::Rc;

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let data = Rc::new(42);
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        println!("{}", data); // ERROR: Rc<i32> cannot be sent between threads safely
    });
}

// FIX: Use Arc instead of Rc for cross-thread sharing
use std::sync::Arc;
let data = Arc::new(42);
tokio::spawn(async move {
    println!("{}", data); // works
});
```

Common non-`Send` types: `Rc`, `Cell`, `RefCell` (without additional wrapping), raw pointers, and MutexGuards held across await points. The fix is usually: replace `Rc` with `Arc`, replace `RefCell` with `Mutex`, and ensure `MutexGuard` is dropped before `.await`. If using `std::sync::MutexGuard` across await, switch to `tokio::sync::Mutex`.

This error occurs when a closure or async block captures a reference that doesn't live long enough for the context it's used in.

```rust
fn make_greeting(name: &str) -> impl Fn() -> String + '_ {
    move || format!("Hello, {}", name) // ERROR without '_ lifetime bound
}

// The returned closure borrows `name`, so the caller must ensure
// `name` outlives the closure. The '_ tells Rust to infer the lifetime.

// Common in async:
async fn process(data: &[u8]) {
    tokio::spawn(async {
        // ERROR: borrowed data might not live long enough
        println!("{:?}", data);
    });
}

// FIX: clone/own the data before spawning
async fn process(data: &[u8]) {
    let owned = data.to_vec();
    tokio::spawn(async move {
        println!("{:?}", owned); // works — owned data moved into task
    });
}
```

`tokio::spawn` requires `'static` lifetime because the spawned task may outlive the calling function. Convert borrowed data to owned data before spawning. This is the most common cause of this error in async Rust.

Type mismatches with `Result` and `Option` usually come from forgetting to unwrap, using `?` in the wrong context, or mixing error types.

```rust
// ERROR: expected `String`, found `Result<String, Error>`
fn read_config() -> String {
    std::fs::read_to_string("config.toml") // returns Result, not String
}

// FIX 1: propagate the error
fn read_config() -> Result<String, std::io::Error> {
    std::fs::read_to_string("config.toml")
}

// FIX 2: use ? operator (requires compatible return type)
fn read_config() -> anyhow::Result<String> {
    let content = std::fs::read_to_string("config.toml")?;
    Ok(content)
}

// ERROR: ? on different error types
fn process() -> Result<(), std::io::Error> {
    let n: i32 = "42".parse()?; // ParseIntError != io::Error
}

// FIX: use anyhow or implement From
fn process() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let n: i32 = "42".parse()?; // anyhow accepts any error type
    Ok(())
}
```

Use `anyhow::Result` for applications (flexible, any error type). Use `thiserror` for libraries (custom error enums with `From` impls). The `?` operator calls `From::from()` to convert between error types automatically.

Rust enforces single ownership. After moving a value, the original variable is invalid. This error catches use-after-move bugs at compile time.

```rust
let s = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s;        // s is moved to s2
println!("{}", s);  // ERROR: value used after move

// Types that implement Copy (integers, bools, chars) are duplicated, not moved
let x = 42;
let y = x;
println!("{}", x); // fine — i32 implements Copy

// Fix 1: Clone
let s = String::from("hello");
let s2 = s.clone();
println!("{}", s);  // fine

// Fix 2: Borrow instead of move
let s = String::from("hello");
let s2 = &s;
println!("{}", s);  // fine

// Common in loops:
let name = String::from("Alice");
for _ in 0..3 {
    greet(name); // ERROR: moved in first iteration
}
// FIX: pass &name or clone inside loop
```

This is fundamental to Rust's memory safety. Move semantics prevent double-free bugs. If you need shared ownership without borrowing, use `Rc<T>` (single-threaded) or `Arc<T>` (multi-threaded).

This cryptic error appears when a closure's inferred lifetime is too restrictive for how it's being used, often in higher-order functions.

```rust
// ERROR: implementation of `Fn` is not general enough
fn apply_to_str(f: impl Fn(&str) -> &str) -> String {
    f("hello").to_string()
}

let result = apply_to_str(|s| &s[0..3]); // lifetime mismatch

// FIX: use explicit higher-ranked trait bounds (HRTB)
fn apply_to_str(f: impl for<'a> Fn(&'a str) -> &'a str) -> String {
    f("hello").to_string()
}
```

The `for<'a>` syntax means "this function works for any lifetime `'a`". Without it, the compiler may infer a specific lifetime that's too narrow. This error is most common when passing closures that borrow from their arguments to generic functions. If the closure doesn't need to return a reference, restructure to return an owned type instead.

This error occurs when an async task holds a non-Send type across an await point, making the entire Future non-Send.

```rust
use std::sync::MutexGuard;

async fn bad_example(mutex: &std::sync::Mutex<Vec<i32>>) {
    let guard: MutexGuard<_> = mutex.lock().unwrap();
    // guard is held across this await point
    some_async_op().await; // ERROR when used with tokio::spawn
    println!("{:?}", *guard);
}

// FIX: drop the guard before awaiting
async fn good_example(mutex: &std::sync::Mutex<Vec<i32>>) {
    {
        let guard = mutex.lock().unwrap();
        println!("{:?}", *guard);
    } // guard dropped here
    some_async_op().await; // safe now
}

// Or use tokio::sync::Mutex which is Send-safe across await
async fn also_good(mutex: &tokio::sync::Mutex<Vec<i32>>) {
    let guard = mutex.lock().await;
    some_async_op().await; // fine — tokio MutexGuard is Send
    println!("{:?}", *guard);
}
```

The fix depends on context: scope the guard so it's dropped before await, use `tokio::sync::Mutex`, or restructure to avoid holding locks across suspension points.

When the compiler cannot infer a generic type, you need to provide it explicitly using turbofish (`::<>`) syntax or type annotations.

```rust
// ERROR: cannot infer type for type parameter `T`
let parsed = "42".parse(); // parse into what?

// FIX 1: turbofish on the method
let parsed = "42".parse::<i32>().unwrap();

// FIX 2: type annotation on the binding
let parsed: i32 = "42".parse().unwrap();

// Common with collect()
let nums = vec!["1", "2", "3"];
let parsed = nums.iter().map(|s| s.parse().unwrap()).collect(); // ERROR
let parsed: Vec<i32> = nums.iter().map(|s| s.parse().unwrap()).collect(); // OK
let parsed = nums.iter().map(|s| s.parse::<i32>().unwrap()).collect::<Vec<_>>(); // Also OK
```

Turbofish is required when the type cannot be inferred from context. It's especially common with `collect()`, `parse()`, `default()`, and `into()`. The `_` placeholder lets the compiler infer part of a type while you specify the rest.

Serde derive macros must be enabled, and all fields in a struct must implement the required traits. This error usually means a missing derive or an incompatible field type.

```rust
// ERROR: the trait bound `MyStruct: Deserialize<'_>` is not satisfied
#[derive(Debug)] // missing Deserialize!
struct MyStruct {
    name: String,
}

// FIX: add serde derives
use serde::{Serialize, Deserialize};

#[derive(Debug, Serialize, Deserialize)]
struct MyStruct {
    name: String,
    #[serde(with = "chrono::serde::ts_seconds")] // custom serializer for non-serde types
    created_at: chrono::DateTime<chrono::Utc>,
}

// Cargo.toml — must enable derive feature
// serde = { version = "1", features = ["derive"] }
```

If a field type doesn't implement `Serialize`/`Deserialize`, you have three options: (1) add a `#[serde(with = "...")]` custom serializer, (2) wrap the type in a newtype and implement the traits, or (3) use `#[serde(skip)]` to exclude the field. Check that `features = ["derive"]` is enabled in Cargo.toml.

This error means the crate is not in Cargo.toml, the feature isn't enabled, or the module path is wrong.

```rust
// ERROR: use of undeclared crate or module `tokio`
use tokio::fs;

// Check 1: Is it in Cargo.toml?
// [dependencies]
// tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }

// Check 2: Is the required feature enabled?
// tokio = { version = "1" }  // missing "fs" feature!
// FIX: tokio = { version = "1", features = ["fs"] }

// Check 3: Module path correct?
// ERROR: use of undeclared module `models`
// Make sure you have:
// src/models.rs OR src/models/mod.rs
// AND in src/main.rs or src/lib.rs:
mod models;
use crate::models::User;

// Check 4: For 2021 edition, extern crate is usually not needed
// But for proc macros, you may still need:
extern crate proc_macro;
```

The Rust 2021 edition auto-imports crates listed in `[dependencies]`. If you renamed a crate with `package = "original-name"`, use the renamed key, not the package name. Run `cargo check` after adding dependencies to verify resolution.

The Rust ecosystem has converged on `thiserror` for library error types and `anyhow` for application error handling. They complement each other.

```rust
// Library code — thiserror for structured, typed errors
use thiserror::Error;

#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum DatabaseError {
    #[error("connection failed: {0}")]
    ConnectionFailed(String),
    #[error("query error: {source}")]
    QueryFailed {
        #[from]
        source: sqlx::Error,
    },
    #[error("record not found: {table}/{id}")]
    NotFound { table: String, id: i64 },
}

// Application code — anyhow for ergonomic error propagation
use anyhow::{Context, Result};

async fn bootstrap() -> Result<()> {
    let config = load_config()
        .context("failed to load configuration")?; // adds context to any error
    let db = connect_db(&config.database_url)
        .await
        .context("database connection failed")?;
    let user = db.find_user(1)
        .await
        .context("failed to find admin user")?;
    Ok(())
}
```

Use `thiserror` when callers need to match on error variants (libraries). Use `anyhow` when you just want to propagate errors with context (applications). The `.context()` method adds human-readable breadcrumbs to error chains — invaluable for debugging.

The builder pattern provides a fluent API for constructing structs with many optional fields, avoiding constructors with dozens of parameters.

```rust
#[derive(Debug)]
pub struct HttpClient {
    base_url: String,
    timeout_ms: u64,
    max_retries: u32,
    headers: Vec<(String, String)>,
}

pub struct HttpClientBuilder {
    base_url: String,
    timeout_ms: u64,
    max_retries: u32,
    headers: Vec<(String, String)>,
}

impl HttpClientBuilder {
    pub fn new(base_url: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        Self {
            base_url: base_url.into(),
            timeout_ms: 30_000,
            max_retries: 3,
            headers: vec![],
        }
    }

    pub fn timeout_ms(mut self, ms: u64) -> Self {
        self.timeout_ms = ms;
        self
    }

    pub fn max_retries(mut self, n: u32) -> Self {
        self.max_retries = n;
        self
    }

    pub fn header(mut self, key: impl Into<String>, value: impl Into<String>) -> Self {
        self.headers.push((key.into(), value.into()));
        self
    }

    pub fn build(self) -> HttpClient {
        HttpClient {
            base_url: self.base_url,
            timeout_ms: self.timeout_ms,
            max_retries: self.max_retries,
            headers: self.headers,
        }
    }
}

// Usage
let client = HttpClientBuilder::new("https://api.example.com")
    .timeout_ms(5000)
    .max_retries(5)
    .header("Authorization", "Bearer token")
    .build();
```

For less boilerplate, use the `derive_builder` or `typed-builder` crates. The builder pattern is idiomatic in Rust because the language lacks default parameter values and function overloading.

The newtype pattern wraps an existing type in a single-field tuple struct to gain type safety and enable trait implementations on foreign types.

```rust
// Without newtype: easy to mix up arguments
fn transfer(from: u64, to: u64, amount: f64) { /* ... */ }
transfer(to_id, from_id, amount); // compiles but wrong!

// With newtype: compiler catches mistakes
struct UserId(u64);
struct Amount(f64);

fn transfer(from: UserId, to: UserId, amount: Amount) { /* ... */ }
// transfer(amount, from, to); // ERROR: type mismatch

// Implement Display for a foreign type
struct Wrapper(Vec<String>);

impl std::fmt::Display for Wrapper {
    fn fmt(&self, f: &mut std::fmt::Formatter) -> std::fmt::Result {
        write!(f, "[{}]", self.0.join(", "))
    }
}

// Use Deref for transparent access to inner type
use std::ops::Deref;
impl Deref for UserId {
    type Target = u64;
    fn deref(&self) -> &u64 { &self.0 }
}

let id = UserId(42);
println!("ID: {}", *id); // Deref to u64
```

Newtypes have zero runtime cost — the wrapper is erased at compile time. Use them for: domain-specific types (UserId, Email, Url), implementing orphan rule traits, and preventing parameter mixups. The `derive_more` crate auto-derives common traits for newtypes.

Tokio provides multiple ways to run concurrent work. Choosing the right one depends on whether the work is CPU-bound, I/O-bound, or needs to be cancelled.

```rust
use tokio::task;

// Spawn independent async task (I/O bound)
let handle = tokio::spawn(async {
    fetch_data().await
});
let result = handle.await?; // JoinHandle returns Result

// Run multiple tasks concurrently, collect all results
let (a, b, c) = tokio::join!(
    fetch_users(),
    fetch_orders(),
    fetch_products(),
);

// Race tasks — first to complete wins, others cancelled
tokio::select! {
    result = fetch_primary() => handle_primary(result),
    result = fetch_fallback() => handle_fallback(result),
}

// CPU-bound work — use spawn_blocking to avoid starving the async runtime
let hash = task::spawn_blocking(move || {
    compute_expensive_hash(&data) // runs on dedicated thread pool
}).await?;

// Fan-out pattern with bounded concurrency
use futures::stream::{self, StreamExt};
let urls: Vec<String> = get_urls();
let results: Vec<_> = stream::iter(urls)
    .map(|url| async move { reqwest::get(&url).await })
    .buffer_unordered(10) // max 10 concurrent requests
    .collect()
    .await;
```

Use `tokio::spawn` for fire-and-forget tasks. Use `join!` when you need all results. Use `select!` for timeouts and fallbacks. Never run CPU-heavy work on the async runtime — always use `spawn_blocking`.

The type-state pattern uses phantom type parameters to encode state transitions in the type system. Invalid state transitions become compile errors.

```rust
use std::marker::PhantomData;

// State types (zero-sized)
struct Draft;
struct Review;
struct Published;

struct Document<State> {
    content: String,
    _state: PhantomData<State>,
}

impl Document<Draft> {
    fn new(content: String) -> Self {
        Document { content, _state: PhantomData }
    }

    fn submit_for_review(self) -> Document<Review> {
        Document { content: self.content, _state: PhantomData }
    }
}

impl Document<Review> {
    fn approve(self) -> Document<Published> {
        Document { content: self.content, _state: PhantomData }
    }

    fn reject(self) -> Document<Draft> {
        Document { content: self.content, _state: PhantomData }
    }
}

impl Document<Published> {
    fn url(&self) -> String {
        format!("https://docs.example.com/{}", self.content)
    }
}

// Usage — invalid transitions are compile errors
let doc = Document::new("Hello".into());
let reviewed = doc.submit_for_review();
// doc.submit_for_review(); // ERROR: doc was moved
// reviewed.url();          // ERROR: no method `url` on Document<Review>
let published = reviewed.approve();
println!("{}", published.url()); // works
```

This pattern is zero-cost at runtime (PhantomData is zero-sized) and catches state machine violations at compile time. Used extensively in embedded Rust for GPIO pin states and protocol implementations.

Clap is the standard Rust CLI argument parser. The derive API generates the parser from struct definitions.

```rust
use clap::{Parser, Subcommand, ValueEnum};

#[derive(Parser, Debug)]
#[command(name = "myapp", version, about = "A sample CLI tool")]
struct Cli {
    /// Input file path
    #[arg(short, long)]
    input: String,

    /// Output format
    #[arg(short, long, default_value = "json")]
    format: OutputFormat,

    /// Verbosity level (-v, -vv, -vvv)
    #[arg(short, long, action = clap::ArgAction::Count)]
    verbose: u8,

    #[command(subcommand)]
    command: Commands,
}

#[derive(Subcommand, Debug)]
enum Commands {
    /// Process the input file
    Process {
        #[arg(long, default_value_t = 4)]
        threads: usize,
    },
    /// Validate the input file
    Validate,
}

#[derive(ValueEnum, Clone, Debug)]
enum OutputFormat {
    Json,
    Csv,
    Table,
}

fn main() {
    let cli = Cli::parse();
    match cli.command {
        Commands::Process { threads } => {
            println!("Processing {} with {} threads", cli.input, threads);
        }
        Commands::Validate => {
            println!("Validating {}", cli.input);
        }
    }
}
```

Clap auto-generates `--help`, `--version`, shell completions, and man pages. Use `#[arg(env = "MY_VAR")]` to read from environment variables as fallback. Add `clap = { version = "4", features = ["derive"] }` to Cargo.toml.

Axum is the leading Rust web framework, built on tokio and tower. It uses extractors to parse requests and tower middleware for cross-cutting concerns.

```rust
use axum::{
    extract::{Path, Query, State, Json},
    http::StatusCode,
    middleware,
    routing::{get, post},
    Router,
};
use serde::{Deserialize, Serialize};
use std::sync::Arc;
use tokio::sync::RwLock;

#[derive(Clone)]
struct AppState {
    db: Arc<RwLock<Vec<User>>>,
}

#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Clone)]
struct User {
    id: u64,
    name: String,
}

#[derive(Deserialize)]
struct Pagination {
    page: Option<u32>,
    per_page: Option<u32>,
}

async fn list_users(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Query(pagination): Query<Pagination>,
) -> Json<Vec<User>> {
    let users = state.db.read().await;
    let page = pagination.page.unwrap_or(1);
    let per_page = pagination.per_page.unwrap_or(20);
    let start = ((page - 1) * per_page) as usize;
    Json(users[start..].iter().take(per_page as usize).cloned().collect())
}

async fn create_user(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    Json(user): Json<User>,
) -> (StatusCode, Json<User>) {
    state.db.write().await.push(user.clone());
    (StatusCode::CREATED, Json(user))
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    let state = AppState { db: Arc::new(RwLock::new(vec![])) };
    let app = Router::new()
        .route("/users", get(list_users).post(create_user))
        .with_state(state);
    let listener = tokio::net::TcpListener::bind("0.0.0.0:3000").await.unwrap();
    axum::serve(listener, app).await.unwrap();
}
```

Axum handlers are regular async functions. Extractors (`State`, `Json`, `Path`, `Query`) parse the request. The order of extractors matters — `Json` must be last because it consumes the body. Use tower middleware for logging, auth, and CORS.

SQLx verifies SQL queries against your database schema at compile time. Queries with typos or wrong column types fail to compile.

```rust
use sqlx::{PgPool, FromRow};

#[derive(FromRow, Debug)]
struct User {
    id: i64,
    email: String,
    name: Option<String>,
    created_at: chrono::DateTime<chrono::Utc>,
}

async fn find_user(pool: &PgPool, id: i64) -> sqlx::Result<Option<User>> {
    // Compile-time verified against live database!
    sqlx::query_as!(User,
        "SELECT id, email, name, created_at FROM users WHERE id = $1",
        id
    )
    .fetch_optional(pool)
    .await
}

async fn create_user(pool: &PgPool, email: &str, name: &str) -> sqlx::Result<User> {
    sqlx::query_as!(User,
        r#"INSERT INTO users (email, name)
           VALUES ($1, $2)
           RETURNING id, email, name, created_at"#,
        email, name
    )
    .fetch_one(pool)
    .await
}

// Setup
#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let pool = PgPool::connect(&std::env::var("DATABASE_URL")?).await?;
    sqlx::migrate!().run(&pool).await?; // run migrations
    Ok(())
}
```

Set `DATABASE_URL` in `.env` for compile-time checking. Use `sqlx prepare` to generate offline query metadata for CI builds without a live database. The `query_as!` macro maps columns to struct fields by name — column count and types must match exactly.

Serde handles most JSON serialization automatically, but real-world APIs need custom enum representations, date formats, and field transformations.

```rust
use serde::{Serialize, Deserialize};
use chrono::{DateTime, Utc};

// Tag enums for clean JSON representation
#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize, Debug)]
#[serde(tag = "type", content = "data")]
enum Event {
    #[serde(rename = "user.created")]
    UserCreated { id: u64, email: String },
    #[serde(rename = "order.placed")]
    OrderPlaced { id: u64, total: f64 },
}
// Serializes as: {"type": "user.created", "data": {"id": 1, "email": "a@b.com"}}

// Custom date format
mod rfc2822_format {
    use chrono::{DateTime, Utc};
    use serde::{self, Deserialize, Deserializer, Serializer};

    pub fn serialize<S>(date: &DateTime<Utc>, serializer: S) -> Result<S::Ok, S::Error>
    where S: Serializer {
        serializer.serialize_str(&date.to_rfc2822())
    }

    pub fn deserialize<'de, D>(deserializer: D) -> Result<DateTime<Utc>, D::Error>
    where D: Deserializer<'de> {
        let s = String::deserialize(deserializer)?;
        DateTime::parse_from_rfc2822(&s)
            .map(|dt| dt.with_timezone(&Utc))
            .map_err(serde::de::Error::custom)
    }
}

#[derive(Serialize, Deserialize)]
struct ApiResponse {
    #[serde(with = "rfc2822_format")]
    timestamp: DateTime<Utc>,
}
```

Enum representations: `#[serde(untagged)]` for union types, `#[serde(tag = "type")]` for internally tagged, `#[serde(tag = "type", content = "data")]` for adjacently tagged. Use `#[serde(with = "...")]` for custom field serialization without implementing Serialize/Deserialize on the type itself.

Rust iterators compose into zero-cost data pipelines. The compiler fuses the entire chain into a single loop — no intermediate collections.

```rust
use std::collections::HashMap;

struct LogEntry {
    level: String,
    message: String,
    timestamp: u64,
}

fn analyze_logs(logs: &[LogEntry]) -> HashMap<String, Vec<&str>> {
    logs.iter()
        .filter(|log| log.timestamp > 1000)
        .filter(|log| log.level == "ERROR" || log.level == "WARN")
        .fold(HashMap::new(), |mut acc, log| {
            acc.entry(log.level.clone())
                .or_default()
                .push(&log.message);
            acc
        })
}

// Chaining with flat_map, enumerate, and windows
let data = vec![vec![1, 2], vec![3, 4], vec![5, 6]];
let result: Vec<(usize, i32)> = data.iter()
    .flat_map(|inner| inner.iter().copied())  // flatten nested vecs
    .enumerate()                               // add index
    .filter(|(_, val)| val % 2 == 0)          // keep evens
    .collect();
// [(1, 2), (3, 4), (5, 6)]

// Partition into two collections
let (evens, odds): (Vec<i32>, Vec<i32>) = (0..10)
    .partition(|x| x % 2 == 0);

// Scan — like fold but yields intermediate values
let running_sum: Vec<i32> = vec![1, 2, 3, 4]
    .iter()
    .scan(0, |state, x| { *state += x; Some(*state) })
    .collect(); // [1, 3, 6, 10]
```

Key methods: `map`, `filter`, `flat_map` for transformation; `fold`, `reduce`, `scan` for accumulation; `take`, `skip`, `step_by` for windowing; `chain`, `zip`, `enumerate` for combination; `partition`, `unzip` for splitting.

The `tracing` crate is the standard for structured, async-aware logging in Rust. It provides spans that track logical operations across async tasks.

```rust
use tracing::{info, warn, error, instrument, Level};
use tracing_subscriber::{fmt, EnvFilter};

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() {
    // Initialize subscriber with env filter
    tracing_subscriber::fmt()
        .with_env_filter(
            EnvFilter::try_from_default_env()
                .unwrap_or_else(|_| EnvFilter::new("info,my_app=debug"))
        )
        .json() // structured JSON output
        .init();

    info!(version = env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION"), "starting server");
    process_request(42).await;
}

// #[instrument] auto-creates a span with function name and arguments
#[instrument(skip(db), fields(user_id = %id))]
async fn process_request(id: u64) {
    info!("processing request");

    match fetch_user(id).await {
        Ok(user) => info!(name = %user.name, "user found"),
        Err(e) => error!(error = %e, "failed to fetch user"),
    }
}

// Outputs structured JSON:
// {"timestamp":"...","level":"INFO","target":"my_app",
//  "span":{"name":"process_request","user_id":"42"},
//  "fields":{"message":"processing request"}}
```

Use `#[instrument]` on async functions for automatic span creation. Use `skip` to avoid logging sensitive fields. Spans propagate across await points, so you get full request traces through concurrent async operations. Pair with `tracing-opentelemetry` for distributed tracing.

Both crates are by the same author (dtolnay) and are designed to be used together — thiserror for libraries, anyhow for applications.

```rust
// thiserror — define structured error types for libraries
use thiserror::Error;

#[derive(Error, Debug)]
pub enum ApiError {
    #[error("not found: {0}")]
    NotFound(String),
    #[error("unauthorized")]
    Unauthorized,
    #[error(transparent)]
    Database(#[from] sqlx::Error),
}

// Callers can match on specific variants
match api_call().await {
    Err(ApiError::NotFound(id)) => /* handle 404 */,
    Err(ApiError::Unauthorized) => /* handle 401 */,
    _ => {}
}

// anyhow — ergonomic error propagation for applications
use anyhow::{Context, Result, bail, ensure};

async fn run() -> Result<()> {
    ensure!(config.port > 0, "port must be positive"); // like assert but returns Err
    let db = connect(&config.db_url)
        .await
        .context("database connection failed")?;
    if db.is_read_only() {
        bail!("database is in read-only mode"); // return Err immediately
    }
    Ok(())
}
```

| Feature | thiserror | anyhow |
|---------|-----------|--------|
| Custom error types | Yes (derive) | No (Box<dyn Error>) |
| Pattern matching | Yes | No |
| Error context | Manual | .context() method |
| Use case | Libraries | Applications |
| Overhead | Zero-cost | One allocation per error |

Rust has three main smart pointer types for heap allocation, each with different ownership semantics.

```rust
use std::rc::Rc;
use std::sync::Arc;

// Box<T> — single owner, heap allocated
let boxed: Box<i32> = Box::new(42);
// Unique ownership, freed when box goes out of scope
// Use for: recursive types, trait objects, large stack values

// Rc<T> — multiple owners, single-threaded
let shared: Rc<String> = Rc::new("hello".to_string());
let clone1 = Rc::clone(&shared); // increment reference count
let clone2 = Rc::clone(&shared);
println!("refs: {}", Rc::strong_count(&shared)); // 3
// NOT thread-safe! Cannot Send across threads.

// Arc<T> — multiple owners, thread-safe
let shared: Arc<String> = Arc::new("hello".to_string());
let clone = Arc::clone(&shared);
std::thread::spawn(move || {
    println!("{}", clone); // safe to use across threads
});
```

| Type | Ownership | Thread-safe | Overhead | Use case |
|------|-----------|-------------|----------|----------|
| Box<T> | Single | Yes (if T: Send) | Allocation only | Trait objects, recursive types |
| Rc<T> | Shared | No | Ref count (cheap) | Graph structures, single-thread sharing |
| Arc<T> | Shared | Yes | Atomic ref count | Cross-thread sharing |

Rule of thumb: prefer owned values on the stack. Use `Box` for dynamic dispatch. Use `Rc` in single-threaded sharing (UI trees, graph nodes). Use `Arc` when sharing across threads. Combine `Arc` with `Mutex`/`RwLock` for shared mutable state.

A goroutine that sends to an unbuffered channel blocks forever if no goroutine reads from it. This is the most common source of goroutine leaks.

```go
// BUG: goroutine leaks if timeout fires first
func fetchWithTimeout(url string) (string, error) {
    ch := make(chan string)
    go func() {
        resp := fetch(url)  // slow network call
        ch <- resp           // blocks forever if nobody reads
    }()
    select {
    case result := <-ch:
        return result, nil
    case <-time.After(2 * time.Second):
        return "", errors.New("timeout")
    }
    // If timeout wins, the goroutine is stuck on ch <- resp forever
}

// FIX: use buffered channel so the send never blocks
func fetchWithTimeout(url string) (string, error) {
    ch := make(chan string, 1) // buffer of 1
    go func() {
        resp := fetch(url)
        ch <- resp // doesn't block even if nobody reads
    }()
    select {
    case result := <-ch:
        return result, nil
    case <-time.After(2 * time.Second):
        return "", errors.New("timeout")
    }
}
```

Another fix is to use `context.WithTimeout` and check `ctx.Done()` in the goroutine. Use `runtime.NumGoroutine()` in tests to detect leaks, or the `goleak` package from Uber.

An interface in Go is a (type, value) pair. An interface holding a nil pointer is NOT equal to nil because the type information is still present.

```go
type MyError struct {
    Code int
}

func (e *MyError) Error() string {
    return fmt.Sprintf("error code: %d", e.Code)
}

func getError() error {
    var err *MyError = nil
    return err // returns interface{type: *MyError, value: nil}
}

func main() {
    err := getError()
    fmt.Println(err == nil) // false! interface is not nil
    // err has type *MyError with nil value — the interface itself is not nil
}

// FIX: return nil directly, not a typed nil pointer
func getError() error {
    var err *MyError = nil
    if err == nil {
        return nil // return untyped nil
    }
    return err
}
```

This gotcha is one of the most FAQ'd Go issues. It affects any function returning an interface type. Always return bare `nil` from functions returning interfaces, never a typed nil pointer. Use `reflect.ValueOf(err).IsNil()` if you must check whether an interface holds a nil pointer at runtime.

Unlike Java's try-with-resources or Python's `with`, Go's `defer` runs when the enclosing function returns, not when the enclosing block ends.

```go
// BUG: all files stay open until the function returns
func processFiles(paths []string) error {
    for _, path := range paths {
        f, err := os.Open(path)
        if err != nil {
            return err
        }
        defer f.Close() // won't close until processFiles returns!
        // With 10000 files, you exhaust file descriptors
    }
    return nil
}

// FIX 1: close manually
for _, path := range paths {
    f, _ := os.Open(path)
    data, _ := io.ReadAll(f)
    f.Close() // close immediately
    process(data)
}

// FIX 2: extract to a function — defer runs at inner function exit
func processFiles(paths []string) error {
    for _, path := range paths {
        if err := processOne(path); err != nil {
            return err
        }
    }
    return nil
}

func processOne(path string) error {
    f, err := os.Open(path)
    if err != nil {
        return err
    }
    defer f.Close() // closes when processOne returns — correct!
    return process(f)
}
```

Defers are stacked (LIFO order) and evaluated when the surrounding function returns. Arguments to deferred calls are evaluated immediately. This means `defer fmt.Println(x)` captures the current value of `x`, not the value at function exit.

Slices in Go are a (pointer, length, capacity) triple. Appending to a slice may or may not allocate new backing memory, leading to subtle aliasing bugs.

```go
// Surprise: modifying a sub-slice can change the original
original := []int{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
sub := original[:3] // [1, 2, 3] — shares backing array!
sub = append(sub, 99)
fmt.Println(original) // [1 2 3 99 5] — original[3] was overwritten!

// Because len(sub)=3, cap(sub)=5, append didn't allocate
// It wrote into the existing backing array

// FIX: use full slice expression to limit capacity
sub := original[:3:3] // length=3, capacity=3
sub = append(sub, 99) // forces new allocation
fmt.Println(original) // [1 2 3 4 5] — unchanged

// Also dangerous: passing slices to functions
func addItem(items []int, item int) []int {
    return append(items, item) // may or may not modify caller's backing array
}

// Rule: treat append's return value as the only valid reference
s := []int{1, 2, 3}
s = append(s, 4) // always reassign to s
```

The three-index slice expression `a[low:high:max]` sets capacity to `max-low`, preventing append from writing into shared backing memory. Use it whenever you create sub-slices that might be appended to independently.

Sending and receiving on an unbuffered channel in the same goroutine deadlocks immediately because the send blocks waiting for a receiver that will never arrive.

```go
// DEADLOCK: send blocks, receive never reached
func main() {
    ch := make(chan int)
    ch <- 42        // blocks forever waiting for receiver
    val := <-ch     // never reached
    fmt.Println(val)
}

// fatal error: all goroutines are asleep - deadlock!

// FIX 1: buffered channel
ch := make(chan int, 1)
ch <- 42        // succeeds — buffer holds the value
val := <-ch     // reads from buffer

// FIX 2: separate goroutine for sender
ch := make(chan int)
go func() {
    ch <- 42
}()
val := <-ch

// SUBTLE DEADLOCK: waiting on a channel that gets closed incorrectly
ch := make(chan int)
close(ch)
ch <- 42 // panic: send on closed channel

// Reading from closed channel returns zero value immediately
val, ok := <-ch // val=0, ok=false
```

Rule: unbuffered channels synchronize goroutines — send and receive must happen in different goroutines simultaneously. Use Go's race detector (`go run -race`) and the `goleak` package to catch these in tests.

Cancelling a context signals intent to stop, but goroutines must explicitly check `ctx.Done()`. Context cancellation doesn't magically interrupt running code.

```go
// BUG: goroutine ignores context cancellation
func longTask(ctx context.Context) error {
    for i := 0; i < 1000000; i++ {
        heavyComputation(i) // never checks ctx
    }
    return nil
}

// FIX: periodically check ctx.Done()
func longTask(ctx context.Context) error {
    for i := 0; i < 1000000; i++ {
        select {
        case <-ctx.Done():
            return ctx.Err() // context.Canceled or context.DeadlineExceeded
        default:
        }
        heavyComputation(i)
    }
    return nil
}

// For I/O operations, pass context to the call
func fetchData(ctx context.Context) error {
    req, _ := http.NewRequestWithContext(ctx, "GET", url, nil)
    resp, err := http.DefaultClient.Do(req) // cancelled if ctx is done
    if err != nil {
        return err // returns if context cancelled
    }
    defer resp.Body.Close()
    return nil
}
```

Always pass context as the first parameter. Always call `cancel()` with defer to prevent resource leaks: `ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(parentCtx, 5*time.Second); defer cancel()`. Not calling cancel leaks the goroutine monitoring the timer.

Go interfaces are satisfied implicitly. There's no `implements` keyword — a type satisfies an interface if it has all the required methods. This means interface compliance can break silently.

```go
type Writer interface {
    Write(p []byte) (n int, err error)
}

type MyBuffer struct {
    data []byte
}

// MyBuffer satisfies Writer — no declaration needed
func (b *MyBuffer) Write(p []byte) (int, error) {
    b.data = append(b.data, p...)
    return len(p), nil
}

// Compile-time check that MyBuffer satisfies Writer
var _ Writer = (*MyBuffer)(nil)

// GOTCHA: pointer receiver vs value receiver matters
type Counter struct { n int }
func (c *Counter) Increment() { c.n++ } // pointer receiver

var c Counter
c.Increment() // Go auto-takes address — fine

var i interface{ Increment() }
i = &c  // OK: *Counter has Increment
// i = c // ERROR: Counter does not have Increment, only *Counter does
```

Use the `var _ Interface = (*Type)(nil)` pattern to verify interface satisfaction at compile time. This is especially important for interfaces defined in other packages where a method signature change would silently break your implementation.

Go's `init()` functions run automatically before `main()`, in dependency order. Multiple `init()` functions per file and per package are allowed, making execution order confusing.

```go
// package db
func init() {
    fmt.Println("db init") // runs before main
    // Common but problematic: global database connection
    pool, _ = sql.Open("postgres", os.Getenv("DATABASE_URL"))
}

// package auth — imports db
func init() {
    fmt.Println("auth init") // runs after db init (depends on db)
}

// package main — imports auth
func init() {
    fmt.Println("main init") // runs last
}

// Order: db init -> auth init -> main init -> main()
```

Problems with init(): (1) Hard to test — init runs before test setup. (2) Hidden dependencies — errors in init crash the whole program at startup. (3) No error return — you're forced to panic or ignore errors. (4) Order depends on import graph, which is implicit.

Prefer explicit initialization functions that return errors: `func SetupDB(url string) (*DB, error)` called from `main()`. This makes dependencies visible, testable, and error-handling explicit. Reserve `init()` for truly simple tasks like registering drivers.

Before Go 1.22, the range loop reused a single variable for all iterations. Closures and goroutines captured the same variable, seeing only the final value.

```go
// BUG (Go < 1.22): all goroutines print the last value
for _, val := range []string{"a", "b", "c"} {
    go func() {
        fmt.Println(val) // captures the loop variable, not the value
    }()
}
// Prints: c c c (or similar — all see final value)

// FIX (Go < 1.22): shadow the variable
for _, val := range []string{"a", "b", "c"} {
    val := val // create new variable per iteration
    go func() {
        fmt.Println(val)
    }()
}

// Or pass as function argument
for _, val := range []string{"a", "b", "c"} {
    go func(v string) {
        fmt.Println(v)
    }(val)
}

// Go 1.22+: FIXED — each iteration has its own variable
// The old behavior is gone when using go 1.22+ in go.mod
```

Go 1.22 changed loop variable semantics to create a new variable per iteration. If your `go.mod` says `go 1.22` or later, this gotcha is gone. But for codebases targeting older versions, the `val := val` shadow pattern is essential.

Go's `encoding/json` package only marshals exported (capitalized) fields. Unexported fields are silently ignored, which is a common source of empty JSON output.

```go
// BUG: all fields unexported — marshals to {}
type user struct {
    name  string
    email string
    age   int
}
u := user{"Alice", "alice@example.com", 30}
data, _ := json.Marshal(u)
fmt.Println(string(data)) // {}

// FIX: export fields and use struct tags for JSON naming
type User struct {
    Name  string `json:"name"`
    Email string `json:"email"`
    Age   int    `json:"age,omitempty"` // omitted if zero value
    // unexported fields are still ignored
    internal string // not in JSON output
}

u := User{Name: "Alice", Email: "alice@example.com", Age: 30}
data, _ := json.Marshal(u)
// {"name":"Alice","email":"alice@example.com","age":30}

// GOTCHA: embedded struct fields are promoted
type Metadata struct {
    CreatedAt time.Time `json:"created_at"`
}
type Post struct {
    Metadata        // embedded — fields promoted to Post level
    Title    string `json:"title"`
}
// Marshals as: {"created_at":"...","title":"..."}
// NOT as: {"Metadata":{"created_at":"..."},"title":"..."}
```

Use `json:"-"` to explicitly exclude an exported field. Use `json:",string"` to marshal numbers as strings. Use `json.RawMessage` for delayed parsing of nested JSON.

Go 1.13 introduced error wrapping with `%w` in `fmt.Errorf`. Using `%v` instead loses the error chain, breaking `errors.Is` and `errors.As`.

```go
import (
    "errors"
    "fmt"
    "os"
)

var ErrNotFound = errors.New("not found")

// BAD: %v formats the error as a string — chain is lost
func bad() error {
    err := os.Open("missing.txt")
    return fmt.Errorf("open failed: %v", err) // wraps as string only
}

// GOOD: %w wraps the error — chain is preserved
func good() error {
    _, err := os.Open("missing.txt")
    return fmt.Errorf("open failed: %w", err) // wraps with chain
}

// errors.Is traverses the chain
err := good()
if errors.Is(err, os.ErrNotExist) {
    fmt.Println("file not found") // matches!
}

err = bad()
if errors.Is(err, os.ErrNotExist) {
    // never reaches here — %v broke the chain
}

// errors.As for type assertion through the chain
var pathErr *os.PathError
if errors.As(err, &pathErr) {
    fmt.Println("path:", pathErr.Path)
}
```

Always use `%w` when you want callers to inspect the underlying error. Use `%v` only when you intentionally want to hide the implementation detail. Go 1.20 added multi-error wrapping: `fmt.Errorf("%w and %w", err1, err2)` wraps both.

Go intentionally randomizes map iteration order to prevent code from depending on it. This catches bugs that would only appear when the hash table resizes.

```go
m := map[string]int{"a": 1, "b": 2, "c": 3}

// Each run produces a different order
for k, v := range m {
    fmt.Printf("%s=%d ", k, v)
}
// Run 1: b=2 c=3 a=1
// Run 2: a=1 b=2 c=3
// Run 3: c=3 a=1 b=2

// FIX: sort keys first for deterministic output
keys := make([]string, 0, len(m))
for k := range m {
    keys = append(keys, k)
}
sort.Strings(keys)
for _, k := range keys {
    fmt.Printf("%s=%d ", k, m[k])
}
// Always: a=1 b=2 c=3

// For JSON output, encoding/json sorts map keys automatically
data, _ := json.Marshal(m) // keys always sorted
```

This matters for: test assertions (use `reflect.DeepEqual` not string comparison), API responses (use `json.Marshal` which sorts keys), configuration generation (sort keys explicitly), and anything producing deterministic output.

sync.Pool recycles objects to reduce allocation pressure, but the GC can clear the pool at any time. Don't store state you can't afford to lose.

```go
import "sync"

// Correct usage: buffer pool for temporary allocations
var bufPool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() any {
        return make([]byte, 0, 4096)
    },
}

func processRequest(data []byte) {
    buf := bufPool.Get().([]byte)
    buf = buf[:0] // reset length, keep capacity
    defer bufPool.Put(buf)

    // Use buf for temporary work...
    buf = append(buf, data...)
    process(buf)
}

// WRONG: using Pool for connection pooling
var connPool = sync.Pool{
    New: func() any {
        conn, _ := net.Dial("tcp", "db:5432") // expensive!
        return conn
    },
}
// GC will close and discard connections unpredictably
// Use a proper connection pool (database/sql, pgxpool) instead
```

sync.Pool is designed for short-lived temporary objects (buffers, encoders, decoders). Objects are kept only until the next GC cycle. For long-lived resources like database connections, use dedicated pool implementations. The New function is called whenever the pool is empty, so it must be cheap.

Go 1.18 introduced generics, but the type constraint system has surprising limitations. `comparable` means `==` and `!=` only, not `<` or `>`.

```go
// comparable allows == and !=
func Contains[T comparable](slice []T, target T) bool {
    for _, v := range slice {
        if v == target {
            return true
        }
    }
    return false
}

// ERROR: cannot use < with comparable
func Max[T comparable](a, b T) T {
    if a > b { return a } // compile error
    return b
}

// FIX: use constraints package or cmp.Ordered
import "cmp"

func Max[T cmp.Ordered](a, b T) T {
    if a > b { return a }
    return b
}
// cmp.Ordered includes: int, float64, string, etc.

// Custom constraint with type union
type Number interface {
    ~int | ~int32 | ~int64 | ~float32 | ~float64
}

func Sum[T Number](nums []T) T {
    var total T
    for _, n := range nums {
        total += n
    }
    return total
}
```

The `~` prefix in type constraints means "any type whose underlying type is X", allowing custom types like `type UserID int` to satisfy `~int`. Use `any` (alias for `interface{}`) for unconstrained generics.

The request context (`r.Context()`) is cancelled when the HTTP handler returns. Background goroutines spawned from a handler that use the request context will be cancelled unexpectedly.

```go
// BUG: background work cancelled when handler returns
func handleWebhook(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    var payload WebhookPayload
    json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&payload)

    go func() {
        // r.Context() is cancelled after handleWebhook returns!
        db.InsertWithContext(r.Context(), payload) // likely fails
    }()

    w.WriteHeader(http.StatusAccepted)
}

// FIX: create a new context for background work
func handleWebhook(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    var payload WebhookPayload
    json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&payload)

    // Use a separate context with its own timeout
    bgCtx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 30*time.Second)
    go func() {
        defer cancel()
        db.InsertWithContext(bgCtx, payload)
    }()

    w.WriteHeader(http.StatusAccepted)
}
```

For production, use a work queue (channel + worker pool) instead of spawning unbounded goroutines per request. The request context should only be used for work that must complete within the request lifecycle.

The Go runtime detects when all goroutines are blocked and no progress can be made. This is a hard deadlock.

```go
// Classic deadlock: main goroutine blocks on channel with no sender
func main() {
    ch := make(chan int)
    val := <-ch // blocks — no goroutine will ever send
}
// fatal error: all goroutines are asleep - deadlock!

// Mutual deadlock with two channels
func main() {
    ch1 := make(chan int)
    ch2 := make(chan int)
    go func() {
        <-ch1       // waits for ch1
        ch2 <- 42   // then sends to ch2
    }()
    <-ch2           // waits for ch2
    ch1 <- 1        // then sends to ch1
    // Both goroutines waiting on each other
}

// Mutex deadlock
var mu1, mu2 sync.Mutex
go func() {
    mu1.Lock()
    mu2.Lock() // blocks
}()
mu2.Lock()
mu1.Lock() // blocks — deadlock
```

The runtime only detects full deadlocks (all goroutines blocked). Partial deadlocks where some goroutines are still running won't be detected. Use `go vet` and the race detector (`-race` flag) to find these. For complex channel patterns, draw the dependency graph to spot cycles.

Go maps are not safe for concurrent read/write. The runtime detects concurrent map access and crashes with a fatal error (not a panic — cannot be recovered).

```go
// FATAL: concurrent map writes
m := make(map[string]int)
for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
    go func(n int) {
        m[fmt.Sprintf("key%d", n)] = n // concurrent write
    }(i)
}
// fatal error: concurrent map writes

// FIX 1: sync.Mutex
var mu sync.Mutex
m := make(map[string]int)
for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
    go func(n int) {
        mu.Lock()
        m[fmt.Sprintf("key%d", n)] = n
        mu.Unlock()
    }(i)
}

// FIX 2: sync.Map (better for read-heavy workloads)
var sm sync.Map
for i := 0; i < 100; i++ {
    go func(n int) {
        sm.Store(fmt.Sprintf("key%d", n), n)
    }(i)
}
val, ok := sm.Load("key42")

// FIX 3: channel-based serialization
type mapOp struct {
    key string
    val int
}
ops := make(chan mapOp, 100)
go func() {
    m := make(map[string]int)
    for op := range ops {
        m[op.key] = op.val
    }
}()
```

Use `sync.RWMutex` when reads vastly outnumber writes. Use `sync.Map` when keys are stable (read-heavy, few deletes). Run with `-race` flag to detect concurrent map access during testing.

This error occurs when a type doesn't satisfy an interface, often because the method is defined on a pointer receiver but you're passing a value.

```go
type Stringer interface {
    String() string
}

type MyType struct {
    Name string
}

// Method on pointer receiver
func (m *MyType) String() string {
    return m.Name
}

// ERROR: MyType does not implement Stringer (String method has pointer receiver)
var s Stringer = MyType{Name: "test"}

// FIX: use pointer
var s Stringer = &MyType{Name: "test"} // works

// This also breaks with slices
type Handler interface {
    Handle()
}

type ConcreteHandler struct{}
func (c *ConcreteHandler) Handle() {}

// ERROR: []ConcreteHandler does not implement []Handler
handlers := []ConcreteHandler{{}, {}}
// var iface []Handler = handlers // doesn't work — Go has no covariance

// FIX: build the interface slice explicitly
iface := make([]Handler, len(handlers))
for i := range handlers {
    iface[i] = &handlers[i]
}
```

Go has no implicit type covariance. A `[]ConcreteType` cannot be assigned to `[]InterfaceType`. This is intentional — it prevents type safety violations that occur with covariant arrays in Java.

Go panics on out-of-bounds slice/array access at runtime. Unlike Rust, this isn't caught at compile time.

```go
// PANIC: index out of range [5] with length 3
s := []int{1, 2, 3}
fmt.Println(s[5])

// PANIC: index out of range [0] with length 0
var empty []int
fmt.Println(empty[0])

// Safe access patterns
func safeGet(s []int, i int) (int, bool) {
    if i < 0 || i >= len(s) {
        return 0, false
    }
    return s[i], true
}

// Recover from panic (use sparingly)
func safeDivide(a, b int) (result int, err error) {
    defer func() {
        if r := recover(); r != nil {
            err = fmt.Errorf("recovered: %v", r)
        }
    }()
    return a / b, nil // panics if b == 0
}

// Common pattern: check length before access
if len(results) > 0 {
    first := results[0]
}

// Nil map read is safe (returns zero), but nil map write panics
var m map[string]int
v := m["key"]     // v = 0, no panic
m["key"] = 1      // PANIC: assignment to entry in nil map
m = make(map[string]int) // always initialize maps
```

Use `recover()` in deferred functions to catch panics, but only at API boundaries (HTTP handlers, worker loops). Don't use panic/recover for normal error handling — that's what error return values are for.

"context deadline exceeded" means an operation took longer than the context's timeout. The hard part is identifying which operation in the chain actually timed out.

```go
// Three levels of timeouts — which one fired?
func handler(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    // Level 1: HTTP server timeout (e.g., ReadTimeout: 10s)

    // Level 2: request-scoped timeout
    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(r.Context(), 5*time.Second)
    defer cancel()

    // Level 3: database query timeout
    dbCtx, dbCancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, 2*time.Second)
    defer dbCancel()

    result, err := db.QueryContext(dbCtx, "SELECT ...")
    if err != nil {
        // err is "context deadline exceeded" but WHICH context?
        if errors.Is(err, context.DeadlineExceeded) {
            // Check which context was cancelled
            if dbCtx.Err() != nil {
                log.Println("database timeout")
            } else if ctx.Err() != nil {
                log.Println("request timeout")
            }
        }
    }
}

// Add timeout info to errors for debugging
func fetchWithTimeout(ctx context.Context) error {
    deadline, ok := ctx.Deadline()
    if ok {
        remaining := time.Until(deadline)
        if remaining < 100*time.Millisecond {
            return fmt.Errorf("context nearly expired, %v remaining", remaining)
        }
    }
    // ... do work
    return nil
}
```

Layer timeouts from outermost (largest) to innermost (smallest). Always check `ctx.Err()` to determine if a context was cancelled vs timed out (`context.Canceled` vs `context.DeadlineExceeded`). Log remaining time at the start of operations to diagnose timeout cascades.

Go's race detector instruments memory accesses at runtime to find data races. It catches bugs that compile successfully but corrupt data.

```go
// DATA RACE: concurrent read and write on shared variable
var count int
for i := 0; i < 1000; i++ {
    go func() {
        count++ // unsynchronized read-modify-write
    }()
}

// Run with: go test -race ./...
// WARNING: DATA RACE
// Write at 0x00c0000a4010 by goroutine 8:
// Previous read at 0x00c0000a4010 by goroutine 7:

// FIX 1: atomic operations
import "sync/atomic"
var count int64
for i := 0; i < 1000; i++ {
    go func() {
        atomic.AddInt64(&count, 1)
    }()
}

// FIX 2: mutex
var mu sync.Mutex
var count int
for i := 0; i < 1000; i++ {
    go func() {
        mu.Lock()
        count++
        mu.Unlock()
    }()
}

// FIX 3: channel serialization
countCh := make(chan int)
go func() {
    total := 0
    for delta := range countCh {
        total += delta
    }
}()
```

Always run `go test -race` in CI. The race detector adds ~2-10x overhead, so it's for testing, not production. It catches reads and writes to the same memory location from different goroutines without synchronization. Use `atomic` for simple counters, `sync.Mutex` for complex state.

Go forbids circular imports. If package A imports B, B cannot import A. This forces clean dependency hierarchies.

```go
// package user
import "myapp/order" // user depends on order

type User struct { ... }
func (u *User) GetOrders() []order.Order { ... }

// package order
import "myapp/user" // order depends on user — CYCLE!

type Order struct { ... }
func (o *Order) GetBuyer() user.User { ... }

// FIX 1: Extract shared types into a third package
// package models
type User struct { ... }
type Order struct { ... }

// FIX 2: Use interfaces to break the dependency
// package order
type Buyer interface {
    ID() int64
    Name() string
}
type Order struct {
    buyer Buyer // interface, no import needed
}

// FIX 3: Dependency injection
// package user
type OrderFetcher func(userID int64) []Order
type UserService struct {
    fetchOrders OrderFetcher // injected, no import needed
}
```

Go's import cycle restriction promotes better architecture. Common patterns: extract shared types to a `types` or `models` package, use interfaces at package boundaries, or use dependency injection. The `internal/` directory convention keeps extracted packages private.

The most common Go runtime panic. It occurs when calling a method on a nil pointer or accessing a field of a nil struct pointer.

```go
// PANIC: nil pointer dereference
type Config struct {
    Database struct {
        Host string
    }
}

var cfg *Config // nil
fmt.Println(cfg.Database.Host) // panic!

// PANIC: nil map
var m map[string]int
m["key"] = 1 // panic: assignment to entry in nil map

// PANIC: nil function call
var fn func()
fn() // panic

// Safe patterns
func getHost(cfg *Config) string {
    if cfg == nil {
        return "localhost"
    }
    return cfg.Database.Host
}

// Initialize maps in constructors
func NewService() *Service {
    return &Service{
        cache: make(map[string]int), // always initialize
        mu:    sync.Mutex{},
    }
}

// Nil-safe method calls (check receiver)
func (c *Config) GetHost() string {
    if c == nil {
        return "localhost"
    }
    return c.Database.Host
}
```

Prevent nil panics by: (1) always initializing maps with `make()`, (2) checking pointers before dereferencing, (3) returning non-nil values from constructors, (4) using the comma-ok idiom for map access. Go doesn't have Rust-style Option types, so nil checks are manual.

Go requires explicit returns on all code paths. The compiler doesn't consider that an `os.Exit()` or a panic means the code after won't execute.

```go
// ERROR: missing return at end of function
func classify(n int) string {
    if n > 0 {
        return "positive"
    } else if n < 0 {
        return "negative"
    }
    // compiler doesn't know the else case is impossible
}

// FIX: add explicit return for all paths
func classify(n int) string {
    if n > 0 {
        return "positive"
    } else if n < 0 {
        return "negative"
    }
    return "zero"
}

// Switch must cover all cases or have default
func describe(day time.Weekday) string {
    switch day {
    case time.Monday:
        return "start of week"
    case time.Friday:
        return "end of week"
    default:
        return "middle of week" // required
    }
}

// Named returns can help with complex functions
func divide(a, b float64) (result float64, err error) {
    if b == 0 {
        err = errors.New("division by zero")
        return // returns named values: (0, err)
    }
    result = a / b
    return // returns named values: (result, nil)
}
```

Named return values are initialized to their zero values, so a bare `return` always works. This is useful for complex error handling but can reduce readability. Go's simplicity means no exhaustive enum matching — always include a default case in switches.

A worker pool limits concurrent goroutines, preventing resource exhaustion from unbounded parallelism. This pattern combines channels, WaitGroups, and context cancellation.

```go
func ProcessItems(ctx context.Context, items []Item, workers int) ([]Result, error) {
    jobs := make(chan Item, len(items))
    results := make(chan Result, len(items))
    var wg sync.WaitGroup

    // Start workers
    for i := 0; i < workers; i++ {
        wg.Add(1)
        go func() {
            defer wg.Done()
            for item := range jobs {
                select {
                case <-ctx.Done():
                    return // stop on cancellation
                default:
                }
                result, err := processItem(ctx, item)
                if err != nil {
                    results <- Result{Err: err}
                    continue
                }
                results <- result
            }
        }()
    }

    // Send jobs
    for _, item := range items {
        select {
        case jobs <- item:
        case <-ctx.Done():
            close(jobs)
            return nil, ctx.Err()
        }
    }
    close(jobs)

    // Wait and collect
    go func() {
        wg.Wait()
        close(results)
    }()

    var out []Result
    for r := range results {
        out = append(out, r)
    }
    return out, nil
}
```

For simpler cases, use `golang.org/x/sync/errgroup` which combines WaitGroup + error propagation + context cancellation in one API. Set `g.SetLimit(n)` to bound concurrency.

The functional options pattern provides a clean API for optional configuration without bloated constructors or config structs.

```go
type Server struct {
    addr    string
    port    int
    timeout time.Duration
    logger  *slog.Logger
    tls     bool
}

type Option func(*Server)

func WithPort(port int) Option {
    return func(s *Server) { s.port = port }
}

func WithTimeout(d time.Duration) Option {
    return func(s *Server) { s.timeout = d }
}

func WithLogger(logger *slog.Logger) Option {
    return func(s *Server) { s.logger = logger }
}

func WithTLS() Option {
    return func(s *Server) { s.tls = true }
}

func NewServer(addr string, opts ...Option) *Server {
    s := &Server{
        addr:    addr,
        port:    8080,                    // sensible default
        timeout: 30 * time.Second,        // sensible default
        logger:  slog.Default(),          // sensible default
    }
    for _, opt := range opts {
        opt(s)
    }
    return s
}

// Clean usage
srv := NewServer("0.0.0.0",
    WithPort(9090),
    WithTimeout(5*time.Second),
    WithTLS(),
)
```

This pattern is used throughout the Go standard library and major libraries (gRPC, zap logger). Benefits: backward-compatible API evolution (new options don't break callers), self-documenting, and sensible defaults without requiring any options.

Go's `http.Handler` interface enables composable middleware. Each middleware wraps the next handler, forming a chain.

```go
// Middleware signature: takes and returns http.Handler
type Middleware func(http.Handler) http.Handler

// Logging middleware
func LoggingMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        start := time.Now()
        // Wrap ResponseWriter to capture status code
        wrapped := &statusWriter{ResponseWriter: w, status: 200}
        next.ServeHTTP(wrapped, r)
        slog.Info("request",
            "method", r.Method,
            "path", r.URL.Path,
            "status", wrapped.status,
            "duration", time.Since(start),
        )
    })
}

type statusWriter struct {
    http.ResponseWriter
    status int
}
func (w *statusWriter) WriteHeader(code int) {
    w.status = code
    w.ResponseWriter.WriteHeader(code)
}

// Auth middleware
func AuthMiddleware(next http.Handler) http.Handler {
    return http.HandlerFunc(func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        token := r.Header.Get("Authorization")
        user, err := validateToken(token)
        if err != nil {
            http.Error(w, "unauthorized", http.StatusUnauthorized)
            return // don't call next
        }
        ctx := context.WithValue(r.Context(), userKey, user)
        next.ServeHTTP(w, r.WithContext(ctx))
    })
}

// Chain helper
func Chain(handler http.Handler, middlewares ...Middleware) http.Handler {
    for i := len(middlewares) - 1; i >= 0; i-- {
        handler = middlewares[i](handler)
    }
    return handler
}

// Usage
mux := http.NewServeMux()
mux.HandleFunc("GET /api/users", listUsers)
handler := Chain(mux, LoggingMiddleware, AuthMiddleware)
http.ListenAndServe(":8080", handler)
```

Middleware executes in the order passed to Chain. The outer middleware (Logging) wraps the inner (Auth). For production, use `chi` or `echo` routers which have built-in middleware chaining and route groups.

Table-driven tests are the idiomatic Go testing pattern. Subtests enable selective execution and parallel running.

```go
func TestParseSize(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name    string
        input   string
        want    int64
        wantErr bool
    }{
        {name: "bytes", input: "100B", want: 100},
        {name: "kilobytes", input: "10KB", want: 10240},
        {name: "megabytes", input: "5MB", want: 5242880},
        {name: "gigabytes", input: "1GB", want: 1073741824},
        {name: "empty string", input: "", wantErr: true},
        {name: "invalid unit", input: "10XB", wantErr: true},
        {name: "negative", input: "-5MB", wantErr: true},
    }

    for _, tt := range tests {
        t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            t.Parallel() // run subtests in parallel

            got, err := ParseSize(tt.input)
            if (err != nil) != tt.wantErr {
                t.Errorf("ParseSize(%q) error = %v, wantErr %v", tt.input, err, tt.wantErr)
                return
            }
            if got != tt.want {
                t.Errorf("ParseSize(%q) = %d, want %d", tt.input, got, tt.want)
            }
        })
    }
}

// Run specific test: go test -run TestParseSize/kilobytes
// Run all: go test -v ./...
```

Benefits: adding a test case is one line in the table, test names appear in output for easy debugging, and `t.Parallel()` speeds up slow tests. For setup/teardown, use `TestMain(m *testing.M)` at the package level or `t.Cleanup()` at the test level.

The `errgroup` package from `golang.org/x/sync` provides a WaitGroup-like API that propagates the first error and cancels remaining work.

```go
import "golang.org/x/sync/errgroup"

func FetchAll(ctx context.Context, urls []string) ([]Response, error) {
    g, ctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
    g.SetLimit(10) // max 10 concurrent goroutines

    responses := make([]Response, len(urls))

    for i, url := range urls {
        i, url := i, url // capture for goroutine (not needed in Go 1.22+)
        g.Go(func() error {
            resp, err := fetchURL(ctx, url)
            if err != nil {
                return fmt.Errorf("fetch %s: %w", url, err)
            }
            responses[i] = resp // safe: each goroutine writes to unique index
            return nil
        })
    }

    if err := g.Wait(); err != nil {
        return nil, err // returns first error; ctx is cancelled for others
    }
    return responses, nil
}

// Pipeline pattern: producer -> processor -> consumer
func Pipeline(ctx context.Context) error {
    g, ctx := errgroup.WithContext(ctx)
    items := make(chan Item, 100)
    results := make(chan Result, 100)

    // Producer
    g.Go(func() error {
        defer close(items)
        return produce(ctx, items)
    })

    // Workers
    for i := 0; i < 5; i++ {
        g.Go(func() error {
            for item := range items {
                result, err := process(ctx, item)
                if err != nil {
                    return err
                }
                results <- result
            }
            return nil
        })
    }

    // Close results when workers done (separate goroutine)
    go func() { g.Wait(); close(results) }()

    return g.Wait()
}
```

errgroup.WithContext creates a derived context that's cancelled when any goroutine returns an error. This provides automatic cancellation of in-flight work. `SetLimit` prevents spawning too many goroutines. It's the standard replacement for hand-rolled worker pools.

Go 1.21 introduced `log/slog` as the standard structured logging package, replacing `log` and third-party loggers for most use cases.

```go
import "log/slog"

// Configure structured JSON logging
logger := slog.New(slog.NewJSONHandler(os.Stdout, &slog.HandlerOptions{
    Level: slog.LevelDebug,
    AddSource: true, // include file:line
}))
slog.SetDefault(logger)

// Basic usage
slog.Info("server started", "port", 8080, "env", "production")
// {"time":"...","level":"INFO","msg":"server started","port":8080,"env":"production"}

// Structured groups
slog.Info("request completed",
    slog.Group("request",
        slog.String("method", "GET"),
        slog.String("path", "/api/users"),
    ),
    slog.Group("response",
        slog.Int("status", 200),
        slog.Duration("latency", 42*time.Millisecond),
    ),
)

// Context-based logger — add fields once, use everywhere
func handleRequest(ctx context.Context, r *http.Request) {
    logger := slog.With(
        "request_id", r.Header.Get("X-Request-ID"),
        "user_id", getUserID(ctx),
    )
    logger.Info("processing request")
    // All subsequent logs include request_id and user_id
    result, err := doWork(ctx)
    if err != nil {
        logger.Error("processing failed", "error", err)
        return
    }
    logger.Info("request completed", "result_count", len(result))
}
```

slog replaces both `log` (unstructured) and `zap`/`zerolog` (third-party structured) for most cases. Use `slog.NewTextHandler` for human-readable development output and `slog.NewJSONHandler` for production. The `slog.With()` method creates a child logger with preset fields.

A production Go HTTP server must handle OS signals and drain in-flight requests before shutting down.

```go
func main() {
    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    mux.HandleFunc("GET /health", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        w.WriteHeader(http.StatusOK)
    })
    mux.HandleFunc("GET /api/data", handleData)

    srv := &http.Server{
        Addr:         ":8080",
        Handler:      mux,
        ReadTimeout:  10 * time.Second,
        WriteTimeout: 30 * time.Second,
        IdleTimeout:  60 * time.Second,
    }

    // Start server in goroutine
    go func() {
        slog.Info("server starting", "addr", srv.Addr)
        if err := srv.ListenAndServe(); err != http.ErrServerClosed {
            slog.Error("server error", "error", err)
            os.Exit(1)
        }
    }()

    // Wait for interrupt signal
    quit := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
    signal.Notify(quit, syscall.SIGINT, syscall.SIGTERM)
    sig := <-quit
    slog.Info("shutting down", "signal", sig)

    // Graceful shutdown with timeout
    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 30*time.Second)
    defer cancel()

    if err := srv.Shutdown(ctx); err != nil {
        slog.Error("forced shutdown", "error", err)
    }
    slog.Info("server stopped")
}
```

`srv.Shutdown()` stops accepting new connections and waits for in-flight requests to complete. The timeout ensures the server doesn't hang forever on slow requests. Set the shutdown timeout longer than `WriteTimeout` to allow active responses to finish. This pattern works with Kubernetes' `preStop` hook and load balancer health checks.

Define repository interfaces to decouple business logic from database implementation, enabling easy testing with mocks.

```go
// Interface — defined where it's consumed, not where it's implemented
type UserRepository interface {
    FindByID(ctx context.Context, id int64) (*User, error)
    FindByEmail(ctx context.Context, email string) (*User, error)
    Create(ctx context.Context, user *User) error
    Update(ctx context.Context, user *User) error
}

// Real implementation
type PostgresUserRepo struct {
    db *sql.DB
}

func (r *PostgresUserRepo) FindByID(ctx context.Context, id int64) (*User, error) {
    var u User
    err := r.db.QueryRowContext(ctx,
        "SELECT id, email, name FROM users WHERE id = $1", id,
    ).Scan(&u.ID, &u.Email, &u.Name)
    if errors.Is(err, sql.ErrNoRows) {
        return nil, ErrNotFound
    }
    return &u, err
}

// Service uses the interface
type UserService struct {
    repo UserRepository
}

func (s *UserService) GetUser(ctx context.Context, id int64) (*User, error) {
    return s.repo.FindByID(ctx, id)
}

// Test mock
type MockUserRepo struct {
    users map[int64]*User
}

func (m *MockUserRepo) FindByID(_ context.Context, id int64) (*User, error) {
    if u, ok := m.users[id]; ok {
        return u, nil
    }
    return nil, ErrNotFound
}

func TestGetUser(t *testing.T) {
    mock := &MockUserRepo{users: map[int64]*User{1: {ID: 1, Name: "Alice"}}}
    svc := &UserService{repo: mock}
    user, err := svc.GetUser(context.Background(), 1)
    // assert...
}
```

Go idiom: define interfaces at the consumer, not the provider. Keep interfaces small (1-3 methods). This avoids the Java pattern of creating interfaces for everything — define them only when you need substitutability (testing, multiple implementations).

Go generics reduce boilerplate for type-safe utility functions that previously required interface{} or code generation.

```go
import (
    "cmp"
    "slices"
)

// Generic Map — transform slice elements
func Map[T any, U any](items []T, fn func(T) U) []U {
    result := make([]U, len(items))
    for i, item := range items {
        result[i] = fn(item)
    }
    return result
}

// Generic Filter
func Filter[T any](items []T, predicate func(T) bool) []T {
    var result []T
    for _, item := range items {
        if predicate(item) {
            result = append(result, item)
        }
    }
    return result
}

// Generic GroupBy
func GroupBy[T any, K comparable](items []T, keyFn func(T) K) map[K][]T {
    groups := make(map[K][]T)
    for _, item := range items {
        key := keyFn(item)
        groups[key] = append(groups[key], item)
    }
    return groups
}

// Usage
type User struct {
    Name string
    Age  int
    City string
}

users := []User{{"Alice", 30, "NYC"}, {"Bob", 25, "LA"}, {"Carol", 30, "NYC"}}

names := Map(users, func(u User) string { return u.Name })
adults := Filter(users, func(u User) bool { return u.Age >= 30 })
byCity := GroupBy(users, func(u User) string { return u.City })

// Standard library generics (Go 1.21+)
slices.Sort(names)                        // sort in place
slices.Contains(names, "Alice")           // true
idx := slices.Index(names, "Bob")         // find index
max := slices.Max([]int{3, 1, 4, 1, 5})  // 5
```

Go 1.21's `slices` and `maps` packages provide generic utilities for common operations. Prefer these over writing your own. Keep generic functions simple — Go generics don't support method-level type parameters or specialization.

A production-ready Go HTTP server template using Go 1.22+ routing patterns.

```go
package main

import (
    "encoding/json"
    "log/slog"
    "net/http"
    "os"
    "os/signal"
    "syscall"
    "time"
)

type CreateUserRequest struct {
    Name  string `json:"name"`
    Email string `json:"email"`
}

func (r CreateUserRequest) Validate() error {
    if r.Name == "" {
        return errors.New("name is required")
    }
    if !strings.Contains(r.Email, "@") {
        return errors.New("invalid email")
    }
    return nil
}

func handleCreateUser(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
    var req CreateUserRequest
    if err := json.NewDecoder(r.Body).Decode(&req); err != nil {
        http.Error(w, "invalid JSON", http.StatusBadRequest)
        return
    }
    if err := req.Validate(); err != nil {
        writeJSON(w, http.StatusBadRequest, map[string]string{"error": err.Error()})
        return
    }
    // ... create user
    writeJSON(w, http.StatusCreated, map[string]string{"status": "created"})
}

func writeJSON(w http.ResponseWriter, status int, data any) {
    w.Header().Set("Content-Type", "application/json")
    w.WriteHeader(status)
    json.NewEncoder(w).Encode(data)
}

func main() {
    mux := http.NewServeMux()
    mux.HandleFunc("POST /api/users", handleCreateUser)
    mux.HandleFunc("GET /api/users/{id}", handleGetUser)
    mux.HandleFunc("GET /health", func(w http.ResponseWriter, r *http.Request) {
        w.WriteHeader(200)
    })

    srv := &http.Server{Addr: ":8080", Handler: mux}
    go func() { srv.ListenAndServe() }()

    quit := make(chan os.Signal, 1)
    signal.Notify(quit, syscall.SIGINT, syscall.SIGTERM)
    <-quit
    ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(context.Background(), 10*time.Second)
    defer cancel()
    srv.Shutdown(ctx)
}
```

Go 1.22 added method-based routing (`GET /path`, `POST /path/{param}`) to the standard library, reducing the need for third-party routers. Use `r.PathValue("id")` to extract path parameters.

